**Over the summer, I had the amazing opportunity of working as a research intern at [Lewis Lab](https://mysite.science.uottawa.ca/jlewis/) in the [Center for Neural Dynamics.](http://www.neurodynamic.uottawa.ca/)**


## Background 
[Weakly Electric Fish](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_fish#Weakly_electric_fish) are often studied in neuroscience as their complex nervous system has fascinated many scientists. These types of fish usually live in very turbid and muddy waters.  These species are specially adapted for this environment as they utilize a sense other than their sight to perceive their environment. Through continually generating an electric field around them and by measuring disturbances in that field, the weakly electric fish gain an electric sense.

## The Goal 
Use machine learning tools to determine the type of environment a fish is placed in by tracking its movement.

## The Project 

Before getting into the details of the machine learning portion of the project, let's dwelve into how the data was processed.

### Getting the Data

I received the data as a directory full of CSVs. The files were simply rows (x,y) coordinates representing the location the fish over time.  Due to a lack of data, I decided on just training the models on two different environment types: high and low water conductivity. To actually train and test models with this data we need to have it all uniform and standardized.

To do so I made a Scikit-Learn pipeline to create the dataset. It reads the CSV files, divides them into equally sized chunks of 999 (x,y). Most could be divided by 999, if not, the pipeline used mean imputation to fill in the rest of the values. Finally, the data is then standardized to a mean of 0 and unit variance. This allows for gradient descent to converge much faster. 

The final result is a dataset of 53k samples. A decent amount but not enough for the traditional train/test/validation split most machine learning projects use. 

Instead, I settled on using K-fold cross validation with k=10. To train the models, you divide the dataset into 10 seperate partitions. You then iterate through the partitions and retain one group as the validation set and the rest as the training set. You record the evaluation scores and discard the model at each iteration. After tweaking the hyperparameters and retraining the models, you train the final model on the complete dataset.

That's enough about the data, let's go into detail about model implementation.


### The Models

I decided on using the two common deep learning architectures for sequence processing: 1-Dimensional Convolutional Neural Networks (1D-CNN) and Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM). All the models were implemented in Keras. 

#### 1D-CNN
ConvNets are a class of neural networks that learn groups of filters. They are usually used for image tasks. Their 1-Dimensional variant allows for sequence processing. 

#### LSTM

LSTMs have been one of the most revolutionary machine learning models for sequence processing. They are composed of LSTM cells with a hidden state that can process data sequentially.

### Results

After several iterations of model architecture and hyperparemeter optimization using `GridSearchCV`, the final trained model was an LSTM model with a validation accuracy of ~85%. This makes it clear that machine learning models can predict rather accurately the type of environment these animals are placed in using only trajectory information.
